Pretoria - Thousands of Unisa workers braved the pouring rain outside the Sunnyside campus in Pretoria to protest against the 6% salary increase offered by the institution.The workers, the majority of them members of the National Education, Health and Allied Workers Union (Nehawu) are demanding a 10% increase.</p> Their initial demand was for a 14% increase across the board backdated to November and implementation of Labour Relations Amendments regarding temporary workers.</p> The union said the institution wasted more than a R100 million of the university's funds by purchasing an IT system for student registration that was unusable and simply difficult for students to use.</p> What angered workers was the reduced offer from 6% to 4.5% after their deadlock was referred to the CCMA for facilitation. </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> Earlier this week, thousands of students were unable to register because staff had embarked on a go-slow. Pretoria NewsThe union said the institution wasted more than a R100 million of the university's funds by purchasing an IT system for student registration that was unusable and simply difficult for students to use.</p> What angered workers was the reduced offer from 6% to 4.5% after their deadlock was referred to the CCMA for facilitation. </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> Earlier this week, thousands of students were unable to register because staff had embarked on a go-slow. Pretoria NewsWhat angered workers was the reduced offer from 6% to 4.5% after their deadlock was referred to the CCMA for facilitation.</p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p>